content.problemStatement:
A **for loop with continue** allows skipping certain iterations of the loop based on a condition. When the `continue` statement is encountered, the loop **immediately jumps to the next iteration**, **skipping the remaining code** for the current iteration. This is useful when filtering data, skipping unwanted values, or optimizing execution.

**Syntax:**  
```java
for (initialization; condition; update) {  
    // Code before continue
    if (skipCondition) {  
        continue; // Skips the rest of the loop body for this iteration  
    }  
    // Code that executes only if continue is not triggered
}
```
---

**Example:**  
```java
class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Loop from 1 to 10
        for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
            if (i % 2 == 0) { // Check if number is even
                continue; // Skip even numbers
            }
            System.out.println(i); // Print only odd numbers
        }
    }
}
```

**Expected Output:**  
```default
1  
3  
5  
7  
9  
```

